42FA504B4D7E4442A9BE0F87E113B25D.description:
Free riders are individuals who benefit
from the work of an interest group without
providing financial support. Interest groups
may deal with this issue by providing
selective benefits, goods and services
that are only available to members, to
encourage more people to join.

D03EA72884834BE59FB606AAFDD28669.description:
Some interest groups have more direct and
more frequent access to important people
in the policy process.

C6D5683FC3894CC99BE04F8240EA7B41.description:
Some interest groups, such as AARP, have
large memberships, are able to mobilize
those members, and possess access to
large financial reserves.

A44D7F514B0046C1B5E38ED828CF7BD1.description:

affects the amount of influence they may have

C4E2DF4897D843D59CE9BD0A2B522AAB.description:
Explain how variation in types
of interest groups and the
resources interest groups

to influence elections and

0B981F3E51A045E7BC32F3C5E0269DA4.description:
In addition to working within party coalitions,
interest groups exert influence through iron
triangles and issue networks that help interest
groups exert influence across political party
coalitions.

32764C877A62416AA6FE68D69E076903.description:
Interest groups may represent very specific
or more general interests, and can educate
voters and office holders, conduct lobbying,
draft legislation, and mobilize membership to
apply pressure on and work with legislators
and government agencies. Interest groups
may also file an amicus curiae brief (a written
document submitted as a “friend of the court”
to provide additional information for justices to
consider when reviewing a case).

7D799717EE374E069367A68F294553D6.description:
Explain the benefits and
potential problems of interest
group influence on elections
and policymaking.

CABA4BAEDDA94938A9C091AEC9A0C190.description:

as a barrier to third-party and independent
candidate success.

FF6DD9C91FD942838D3E47B5D99C43D3.description:
In comparison to proportional systems, winnertake-all voting districts serve as a structural
barrier to third-party and independent
candidate success. Winner-take-all voting
advantages the two-party system in the U.S.

5AB46BE2A4AE4F53A8B65B5A8FA227FF.description:
Straight ticket voting refers to individuals
who vote for all of the candidates from one

C2BF8C33F30F4155BE53296461129CA5.description:
Prospective voting refers to individuals who
vote based on predictions of how a party or
candidate will perform in the future.

3B4ADADF8F104D7895E057180E9DFF12.description:
Retrospective voting refers to individuals
who decide whether the party or candidate
in power should be reelected based on the
recent past.

68350028306542CA8C35DCD9C123EFCE.description:
Rational choice voting refers to individuals
who base their decisions on what is
perceived to be in their best interest.

government involvement in social issues

B158D0A90A324E078DB0013CED69A0D8.description:

social issues.

F6600F2C36684B04AECF62438F92E320.description:
Libertarian ideologies generally favor little
national or state government involvement
except when national or state government is
protecting private property or individual liberty.

E912458A1C024D2F8FB8B321771BFB34.description:
Conservative ideologies generally favor less
national government involvement to address
some social issues such as education and
public health, with more responsibility for these
issues left to state governments.

EF347984EA88464CA561219B114CA23C.description:
Liberal ideologies generally favor more national
government involvement to address some
social issues such as education and public
health, with less responsibility for these issues
left to state governments.

34F13747A36D432DAF14949CB976A154.description:
Explain how political
ideologies vary on the
role of the government in
addressing social issues.

6D9EAAAFB4C44CA786F9762582EEBA51.description:
Monetary policy consists of actions taken
by the Federal Reserve (the Fed) to influence
interest rates which affect broader economic
conditions. The Fed is an independent agency
which seeks to achieve maximum employment
and price stability

196F372A89FF47DDA273C0DEC6E67C66.description:
Fiscal policy consists of actions taken by
Congress and the president to influence
economic conditions and includes Keynesian
and supply-side positions.

6370FE399A39491A8203138BCF17C6C0.description:
Explain how fiscal and
monetary policy actions
influence economic
conditions.

46C491CE000D41D78E8B1A538F8AF798.description:
Liberal ideologies favor more governmental
regulation of the marketplace, conservative
ideologies favor fewer regulations, and
libertarian ideologies favor little or no regulation
of the marketplace beyond the protection of
property rights and voluntary trade.

5FA0FD8A66E341258DB41240C6FB2427.description:
Explain how different political
ideologies affect the role of
government in regulating the
marketplace.

EADA142E80294A4F928DFDE7F4562E78.description:
The balancing dynamic of individual liberty and
government efforts to promote stability and
order has been reflected in policy debates and
their outcomes over time.

E339F077D4484591A29E6CC6E4194AB8.description:
Because the U.S. is a democracy with a diverse
society, public policies generated at any given
time reflect the attitudes and beliefs of citizens
who choose to participate in politics at that time.

3B73541DF2144A10A84AD7B9F4A03C64.description:
Major political events can influence the

which is an example of political socialization.
Political socialization, in turn, influences
political ideology.

ideology.

73EC92B02C19416E97DAE045D649DFCD.description:

Events on Ideology

59F9B11F0AB645DDABBCB124055ABC08.description:
Generational effects (experiences shared
by people of a common age) and life cycle
effects (experiences a person encounters
during different life stages) contribute to the
development of a person’s political ideology.

6FA0770FCC7A4EF78E028ECEB8E99F44.description:
Explain how social factors
impact political ideology.

77924E0B82824139994C30A1F6006A57.description:
U.S. political culture is defined by its
democratic ideals, principles, and core values.
As a result of globalization, U.S. political culture
has both influenced and been influenced by the
values of other countries.

9253E906A23A41269A2093EFC2EDA7FE.description:
Political socialization refers to the process
by which individuals develop political
beliefs, values, opinions, and behaviors.
Family, schools, peers, media, and social
environments (including civic and religious
organizations) contribute to the development
of an individual’s political attitudes and values
through the process of political socialization.

1B70835F1C494974A6849D5DE3323EED.description:
Explain how cultural
factors influence political
socialization.

E3B18AD75BF547F28EBA411223A35EB3.description:
Different interpretations of core values,
including individualism (each person has the
ability to shape their life and destiny through
the choices they make), equality of opportunity
(all people are given an equal chance to
compete), free enterprise (the market
determines prices, products, and services), and
rule of law (every person, even those in power,
must follow and is accountable to the same
laws that govern all), affect the relationship
between citizens and the federal government
and that citizens have with each other.

08B66298D6CE423596DD97A13E9C9062.description:
Explain the relationship
between core beliefs of U.S.
citizens and attitudes about
the role of government.

68154FE1370746AA94F52F1A74DE1E44.description:
American Attitudes
About Government
and Politics

3296A50E33A54E9191B922C8640FF284.description:
Affirmative action refers to policies intended to
address workplace and educational disparities
related to race, ethnic origin, gender, disability,
and age. Supreme Court debate has focused
on whether affirmative action is protected by
the equal protection clause of the Fourteenth
Amendment to the Constitution.

21AC44C6ACCB4F74905902CB04DC5722.description:
Describe Supreme Court

action policies.

AFEA3DFF66544CAAABF7E76565525ACC.description:

same restaurants, hotels, schools, etc., as
the majority white population

D9EC520EE3F348639B28FC1C50BB9E5B.description:
Title IX of the Education Amendments Act

4F1F57EEBF59405E8FE3938CA09D9BC0.description:
The Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits
discrimination in public places, provides
for the integration of schools and other
public facilities, and makes employment
discrimination illegal.

41B3EBD91B214C0CA08D4466E285D0CD.description:

6EBC4FE48A5D4F1990AEE5921029F24B.description:
Explain how the government

The National Organization for Women and

Dr. Martin Luther King’s “Letter from

The civil rights movement, the women’s rights
movement, and advocacy for LGBTQ rights are

E8FE57A4D9194427A75AC78272695AF5.description:
Civil rights protect individuals from
discrimination based on characteristics such
as race, national origin, religion, and sex; these
rights are guaranteed to all persons under the
due process and equal protection clauses
of the U.S. Constitution, as well as acts of
Congress.

607879B13BD849F2B4BB896E1040E81E.description:
Explain how constitutional
provisions have supported
and motivated social
movements.

C0FC7BB045AA4A48A5F6FA0230FE6931.description:
While a right to privacy is not explicitly named
in the Constitution, the Supreme Court, in
Griswold v. Connecticut (1965), interpreted
the due process clause to protect the right of
privacy from government infringement. In
Roe v. Wade (1973), the Supreme Court held
that the application of substantive due process
further extended the privacy right to abortion.
The Supreme Court’s decision in Dobbs v.
Jackson Women’s Health Organization
(2022) overturned Roe v. Wade, holding that
the Constitution does not confer a right
to abortion, leaving decisions about the
regulation of abortion to legislatures. The
actions that are protected by the right to
privacy and substantive due process continue
to be debated.

01460887A36444D992C663E33D1CD9B7.description:
Over time, the Supreme Court has recognized
constitutionally protected rights that are not
explicitly listed in the Bill of Rights. These
unenumerated rights include the right to
privacy. Justices and scholars have drawn on
several arguments to defend the existence
of unenumerated rights. Some argue that
an unenumerated right is implied by certain
amendments that assume the existence
of such rights. Others argue that the Ninth
Amendment, which states that individuals have
protected rights beyond those listed in the first
eight amendments, provides support for the
existence of unenumerated rights.
In a range of cases, the Supreme Court has
used substantive due process to examine
whether government laws and actions are
arbitrary infringements of individual rights.

29FC10B5A2524D9AB7281FFBEB0AFC52.description:
Explain the extent to which
the government is limited
by substantive due process
from infringing upon
individual rights.

83B367EE6BDA4B3FA6EC9FA2400F9133.description:
Amendments:
Due Process and the
Right to Privacy

FF03C2FE08F447E78AA0DF7F3C89485C.description:
Procedural due process also protects the
rights of the accused during a trial. The Bill of
Rights guarantees the right to an attorney and
protection from unreasonable searches and
seizures. The exclusionary rule, as decided by
the Supreme Court, stipulates that evidence
illegally seized by law enforcement officers in
violation of the suspect’s Fourth Amendment
rights (including the right to be free from
unreasonable searches and seizures) cannot
be used against that suspect in criminal
prosecution.

222201B519C442F1BE583F33A8ADC87B.description:
Limitations placed on bulk collection of
telecommunication metadata (Patriot and
USA Freedom Acts)

81D91FB5AD5B460F92E3AEFE12AC9D4D.description:
Protection against warrantless searches
of cell phone data under the Fourth
Amendment

AEE130EB0B894E3FB72DF586F51FBB26.description:
The right to legal counsel, speedy and
public trial, and an impartial jury

78F32D30D8084DC882976DF995DF13A8.description:
Procedural rights of the accused and the
prohibition of unreasonable searches and
seizures are intended to ensure that individual
liberties are not eclipsed by the need for social
order and security, including:

DBA5AB6F78444FB59E56CCE6E8153004.description:
Procedural due process requires that
government officials use methods that are
not arbitrary when making and carrying out
decisions affecting constitutionally protected
rights. These procedural due process
protections are reinforced by key protections
enshrined in other provisions of the Bill of
Rights and key legal doctrines established
by the Supreme Court. For example, the
Miranda rule requires accused persons to
be informed of some procedural protections
found in the Fifth and Sixth Amendments prior
to interrogation. However, these procedural
protections are not absolute. A public safety
exception has been sanctioned by the Court
that allows unwarned interrogation to stand as
direct evidence in court.

FE288861E0AB46B3A19DC5741628DD31.description:
The Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments include
clauses which state that the government may
not infringe on a person’s right to life, liberty,
or property without due process of law. The
due process clause in the Fifth Amendment
applies to the national government and the due
process clause in the Fourteenth Amendment
applies to states. Some government interests
may justify the restriction of individual rights;
for example, speech can be limited when it is
shown to present a danger to public safety.

B3D2A4AA5C1D476F9AE2CCE9B4419544.description:
Explain the extent to which
the government is limited
by procedural due process
from infringing upon
individual rights.

55076EB105CC463A80317E77293DDDC6.description:
Amendments:
Due Process and the
Rights of the Accused

0AA3CFAF3F924B889DC6E0C18090BE61.description:
The doctrine of selective incorporation has
imposed limitations on state regulation of civil
liberties by extending select protections of
the Bill of Rights to the states through the due
process clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.

F85F95D5562A403EA031BD0B97E34D9B.description:
Explain the implications of
the doctrine of selective
incorporation.

AC1E7BBFE86647DF9DF65BE303B72626.description:
The debate about the Second and Fourth
Amendments involves concerns about public
safety and whether or not the government
regulation of firearms or collection of digital
metadata promotes or interferes with public
safety and individual rights.

ADA34C121D9447659644E937207A5AE4.description:
Court decisions defining cruel and unusual
punishment involve interpretation of the Eighth
Amendment and its application to death
penalty statutes.

C68A2AEEF9364BD8A59600F289FB3F28.description:
Explain how the Supreme
Court has attempted to
balance claims of individual
freedom with laws and
enforcement procedures
that promote public order
and safety.

AA2D9E6F2A44461689168A5EAB73B7BA.description:
Amendments: Balancing
Individual Freedom with
Public Order and Safety

D34F1049B71544EABCA4F2341B651232.description:
The Supreme Court’s decisions on the Second
Amendment rest upon its constitutional
interpretation of the right to bear arms.

75F2278C12744AE0A55023B3EB3AD555.description:
Explain the extent to which
the Supreme Court’s
interpretation of the Second
Amendment reflects a
commitment to individual
liberty.

7218F52CE87B4ACF8B555307729A3765.description:
Second Amendment:
Right to Bear Arms

18352A3953DF4B0087113675C5D3FC00.description:
The Supreme Court bolstered the freedom
of the press, affirming support for a heavy
presumption against prior restraint even in
cases involving national security.

D0AA3577BF904886980D68CF5D525764.description:
Explain the extent to which
the Supreme Court’s
interpretation of the First
Amendment reflects a
commitment to individual
liberty.

298F79363E964622839DB0E5ECA53E0C.description:
First Amendment:
Freedom of the Press

071098B03EB4491580EFF68129B64BF5.description:
Restrictions on speech that create a clear
and present danger and subsequent
interpretations which have refined those
restrictions.

F5C31337B8144145884EF1E43B7CF1B9.description:
Protections against defamation (language
that harms the reputation of another)
including libel (written communication) and
slander (oral communication).

660E0FA604A34F82BBC57ABE0CDF9841.description:
Limitations on some obscene and
offensive communication.

EB3FBA7064D343E9BCEAC93B9112AD62.description:
Time, place, and manner regulations that
impose restrictions such as limits on the
time of day an event can be held, limits on
where an event can be held, and limits on
the noise levels at an event

F439FC3E59F4406D8D28BF2357AD87DD.description:
Efforts to balance social order and individual
freedom are reflected in interpretations of the
First Amendment that limit speech, including:

F455972104D242798E004CE5E49A5572.description:
The Supreme Court has held that speech,
including symbolic speech (nonverbal action
that communicates an idea or belief), is
protected by the First Amendment.

17B010AF7ABD4A9E9FC86F27F62E1CB7.description:
Explain the extent to which
the Supreme Court’s
interpretation of the First
Amendment reflects a
commitment to free speech.

9DA11DF61B2E46E8907B8E2082FA1B86.description:
The interpretation and application of the First
Amendment’s establishment and free exercise
clauses reflect an ongoing tension between
government power to make law and an
individual’s right to religious freedom.

41F4B2FFD8874298BDAFE128BA976161.description:
Explain the extent to which
the Supreme Court’s
interpretation of the First
Amendment reflects a
commitment to religious
liberty.

5C84176C365842BCAF6DA3CC19FF59F7.description:
The Bill of Rights consists of the first ten
Amendments to the Constitution, which
enumerate the liberties and rights of individuals.

BBF4E2705BF443CABA2808B46322F602.description:
Describe the rights protected
in the Bill of Rights.

5CF8D4CA6B0840B99D836AFDC2757E24.description:
The application of the Bill of Rights is
continuously interpreted by the courts.

5FCD30F34BA14E39BD17ED986BDDA406.description:
Civil liberties are constitutionally established
guarantees and freedoms that protect citizens,
opinions, and property against arbitrary
government interference.

F509239793894D61A7EFDD7870101D06.description:
The U.S. Constitution includes a Bill of Rights
specifically designed to protect individual
liberties and rights.

48A6400CEA984560AB33D21853D33DF6.description:
Explain how the U.S.
Constitution protects
individual liberties and rights.

23A45EEB3D6945D28E3E0518BBA35EE5.description:
National policymaking is constrained by the
sharing of powers between the three branches.

575E5555603B434BB399575CE44E9BB6.description:
The allocation of powers among the three
branches of government creates multiple
access points for stakeholders and institutions
to influence public policy.

B3C643D9344F40739CD3A878F9900C2F.description:
Explain how the distribution
of powers among the three
branches of government
impacts policymaking.

5EB21321E53E4B088957A7F7576B78C5.description:
Formal and informal powers of Congress, the
president, and the courts over the bureaucracy
are used to maintain its accountability.

43AF0158FB864642A9A6EF21C02C6A80.description:
Explain the extent to which
governmental branches
can hold the bureaucracy
accountable given the
competing interests of
Congress, the president, and
the federal courts.

B33C0572C88041B7BC29BCDC57F22913.description:
Policy and the
Branches of
Government

B104CF134FCE49C4BF30F8C72B653BAA.description:
Compliance monitoring ensures that funds are

followed. Compliance monitoring can pose a
challenge to policy implementation.

027F3075F43040D28917FDB90712DF57.description:
Presidential ideology, authority, and influence

1E94B963158F4DE6BB211E10B2530A55.description:
Explain how the president

branch agencies and
departments carry out
their responsibilities in
concert with the goals of the

As a means to curtail the use of presidential

021AB31EC8A94C5E824FA4D0AD2CD2DB.description:
Power of the purse (the ability of Congress

or withholding funds)

594D489AEF574176A98E0218E35B0D95.description:
Investigation and committee hearings of

568C10E8209940C38DCE941DB414CED6.description:
Review, monitoring, and supervision of

E9EF7B37B9094B688EDCBB32C25EDE5F.description:
Congressional oversight of the bureaucracy

F79CF3E7B8AD4B93A05240FAA401684B.description:
Explain how Congress

The federal bureaucracy uses discretionary
power as delegated by Congress to interpret

54A3C201D8654EC1A6BA7D620E26F30B.description:

The civil service primarily uses a merit system

professionalism, specialization, and neutrality,

Creating issue networks (temporary
coalitions that form to promote a common
issue or agenda)

780AB548348A4B839E8670E91807F06B.description:
Forming iron triangles (alliances of
congressional committees, bureaucratic

prominent in specific policy areas)

BEF28C9E85A64F9F8D562968FD16E62F.description:
The federal bureaucracy is composed of
departments, agencies, commissions, and
government corporations that implement
policy by:

2781263DD2C04721A7C462ED21D3C008.description:
Explain how the
bureaucracy carries out the
responsibilities of the federal
government.

6C96D97BCC374A359AA616505D6FBDEE.description:
Enacting legislation to limit the cases the
Supreme Court can hear on appeal by
removing the court’s jurisdiction over a case

C14397A6CEF042A19CE50D550E243E15.description:
The president and states delaying
implementation of a Supreme Court decision

C9E517EAAC4548A38148B281FC9DF3BE.description:
Judicial appointments and confirmations

the court

87183A871BB04083B8E4B820F49561B5.description:
Congressional legislation to modify the

EE1263570A9146518E8ABB6D23C7A965.description:
Restrictions on the Supreme Court are

5FD0C0804FE54D4F90E5B96250A25438.description:
Explain how other branches
in the government can limit
the Supreme Court’s power.

31767442645C4B719DEF99F7BACCE47F.description:
Judicial restraint asserts that judicial
review should be constrained to decisions
that adhere to current Constitutional and
case precedent.

7CB4A1DA35F2448CA56F823E3F50611C.description:
Judicial activism asserts that judicial
review allows the courts to overturn
current Constitutional and case precedent
or invalidate legislative or executive acts.

EBA96604E0B149E3854D071912BE59F1.description:
Political discussion about the Supreme Court’s
power is illustrated by the ongoing debate over
differing interpretations of judicial review.

646EAC5F69E04FFF8D18512B64F38554.description:
Explain how the exercise of
judicial review can lead to
debate about the Supreme
Court’s power.

B3986902BEF743F8B69BECF3093F2EE9.description:
Life tenure for justices allows the court to
function independent of the current political
climate. As a result of this independence, the
Court can deliver controversial or unpopular
court decisions, which in turn can lead to
debate about the court’s power.

BCFE632339C247BE9B969CAA6308A417.description:
Explain how life tenure can
lead to debate about the
Supreme Court’s power.

4233347C57CC48EF946EB10E8BB53275.description:
Ideological changes in the composition of the
Supreme Court due to presidential appointments
have led to the Court’s establishing new or
rejecting existing precedents.

8CBAE82BD1A9472F8C0225CA0CEA0C23.description:
Stare decisis (the legal doctrine under which
courts follow legal precedents when deciding
cases with similar facts) plays an important role
in judicial decision making.

39300CA21BA44F1A8115984A8E32BFB9.description:
Explain the role of legal
precedent in judicial decision
making.

18C35F93B3D94DD3A250F0B7873EC806.description:
The Role of the
Judicial Branch

The foundation for powers of the judicial

046A4899EAE84467B623AD669EDECFFF.description:
Explain the principle of judicial
review and how it checks the
power of other branches.

8467E2BF8B2843ADA8D305AB4383C3E1.description:
Nationally broadcast State of the Union
messages and the president’s bully pulpit
are tools for agenda setting that use the
media to influence public views about
which policies are the most important.

9F22E401396643FE936B2CA4388F9891.description:
Modern technology, such as social media,
allows for rapid responses to political issues.

9F640E3C42E84FBFB9A31CDD2FF3D404.description:
The impact of presidential communication has
increased with advances in communication
technology.

3E852F302DF5413B9159886DBCC93985.description:
Explain how communication
technology has changed the
president’s relationship with
the national constituency and
the other branches.

EB9AF2A00A054D3BACB5F4271233A0CF.description:
Different perspectives on the presidential role,
ranging from a limited to a more expansive
interpretation and use of power, continue to
be debated in the context of contemporary
events.

0B8DDB4305F94094B557848DAACF9942.description:
Passage of the Twenty-Second Amendment,
which established presidential term limits,
demonstrates concern about the expansion of
presidential power.

108F7651FC174BCDB95CD21D0AF32AF9.description:
Federalist No. 70 offers justification for a
single executive by arguing a strong executive
is “essential to the protection of the country
against foreign attacks, to the steady
administration of the laws, to the protection of
property, and to the security of liberty.”

06DAB2B992964D3AB54238FAAB37ABE8.description:
Explain how presidents have
interpreted and justified their
use of formal and informal
powers.

A445BCEACFDD4955902931B49BDEF354.description:
Policy conflicts with the congressional
agenda (the formal list of policies Congress
is considering at any given time) can lead
the president to use executive orders and
directives to the bureaucracy to address the
president’s own agenda items.

F15AC9FF721548F5BCAA6FD777D287AF.description:
Senate confirmation is an important check
on appointment powers, but the president’s
longest lasting influence lies in life-tenured
judicial appointments.

406DD3E258E04823B2A8193C215C6748.description:
Supreme Court Justices, Court of Appeals
judges, and District Court judges

F75C342B5B3E413DAD69CCD22D13C328.description:
Some positions within the Executive Office
of the President

D04426E5DF9A42C58A7C9E9FB2685A6D.description:
Senate confirmation is an important check
on appointment powers but there can be a
potential for conflict based on who is chosen
by the president for appointments, including:

7A5E58CC4C6B47C785487BFFA58D6807.description:
Explain how the president’s
agenda can create tension
and frequent confrontations
with Congress.

82CCFC225FB64B72BD0B9C7A4642A03A.description:
Signing statements are informal powers
that inform Congress and the public of the
president’s interpretation of laws passed
by Congress and signed by the president.

1DEADE6D3B5A4668AF83FA9660DBC10D.description:
Executive orders allow the president to
manage the federal government and are
implied by the president’s vested executive
power or by power delegated by Congress.

AC62D63F5A484880AD20EF790E34A8E3.description:
Bargaining and persuasion are informal
powers that enable the president to secure
congressional action.

61BC82AC4AC64FFBA03E86318980203D.description:
Foreign policy powers that influence
relations with foreign nations are both
formal (commander-in-chief and treaties)
and informal (executive agreements).

0E5328A14BAD4727A6E243D02F2DF6F5.description:
Vetoes and pocket vetoes are formal
powers that enable the president to check
Congress, but vetoes can be overridden
with a 2/3 vote while pocket vetoes cannot
be overridden with a 2/3 vote.

894045CB982E46F2A72D3803C56DE7C7.description:
The powers of the president include both
formal and informal powers.

C1AC8067E2F14D2CB1B162DE959491D5.description:
Presidents use powers and perform functions
of the office, with support from the Vice-President, Cabinet, and Executive Office of the
President, to accomplish a policy agenda.

2B6D6FB58DB94CAABAD87F69D7A4D899.description:
Explain how the president
can implement a policy
agenda.

5F0C3D47FAC14763BAD4769880CDF537.description:
Roles and Powers
of the President

15AA6112BCEA465A86735787DF7F513F.description:
A politico uses a combination of these role
conceptions.

F3B419B082514948900FC6020A471A43.description:
A representative acting as a delegate sees
themselves as an agent of those who
elected them and will vote on issues based
on the interests of their constituents.

561B048CF6074638AED029C2D5E64869.description:
A representative who conceives of their
role as a trustee will vote on issues based
on their own knowledge and judgement.

781BD1F5A29744CEBEC71D70F085B733.description:
Accountability to constituents in each chamber
is affected by how representatives perceive
their roles.

CD5F2D63CC6F4D1D87C6288B92AAC636.description:
Elections that have led to a divided government
(when one party controls the presidency and
the other party controls at least one of the
chambers of Congress) can lead to more
intense partisanship. This partisanship can
result in members of Congress voting against
presidential initiatives and appointments,
especially those of a lame duck president.

28A431C845BA4977B1262C8205876B21.description:
Gerrymandering, redistricting, and unequal
representation of constituencies have been
partially addressed by Supreme Court cases
that opened the door for equal protection
challenges to redistricting.

EDAA44AEAED3460B9B871985EC1A6A30.description:
Congressional behavior and governing
effectiveness are influenced by ideological
divisions between political parties. Partisan
voting (when members of Congress vote based
on their political party affiliation) and polarization
(when political attitudes move toward ideological
extremes) can lead to gridlock (a situation in
which no congressional action on legislation can
be taken due to a lack of consensus).

03F66FACEBAD4EB6A19F39843D1F8907.description:
Explain how congressional
behavior is influenced
by election processes,
partisanship, and divided
government.

BA831747711F43B68CA6ED651F2EEEF6.description:
Pork-barrel legislation (funding for a local
project in a larger appropriation bill) and
logrolling (exchange of political favors among
legislators, such as trading votes, to gain
support for legislation) affect the legislative
process in both chambers.

715E8167B6BC4B9BB62C1765BA8F3E85.description:
Discretionary spending is approved on
an annual basis for defense spending,
education, and infrastructure. As
entitlement costs grow, discretionary
spending opportunities will decrease
unless tax revenues increase, or the
budget deficit increases.

859318EAB6F3416F84A991C53AC87CDA.description:
Mandatory spending is required by law
for entitlement programs such as Social
Security, Medicare, and Medicaid.

35339D8E6E3D43EB866D1EECA04944A8.description:
Congress must generate a budget that
addresses both mandatory and discretionary
spending.

06C0C513825D484A8C8822BDFD99B309.description:
When a bill passed by both chambers
on the same topic has variation in its
wording, a conference committee meets to
reconcile those differences.

AC42E872B6D042649C710C5AC91E9197.description:
In the Senate, bills are typically brought to the
floor by unanimous consent, but a Senator
may request a hold on a bill to prevent it from
getting to the floor for a vote. During debate,
a Senator can use the filibuster (a tactic to
prolong debate and delay or prevent a vote
on a bill) or make a motion for cloture (a
procedure to end a debate).

280C02BAAE404501BF3E107FF3979D5D.description:
In the House, the Speaker is elected by a
majority of members and presides over the
legislative work in the House. All revenue
bills must originate in the House. Rules for
debate in the House on a bill are established
by the Rules Committee. The House can
form a Committee of the Whole in order
to expedite debate on bills. An individual
representative in the House can file a
discharge petition to have a bill brought to
the floor for debate, but it is rarely done.

F6C682C839984F149F752C2C074D0E30.description:
Chamber-specific rules and procedures affect
the legislative process.

BE77E94131D242D7957BAF7C40C286BE.description:
Both chambers refer bills to committees, which
conduct hearings and debate and mark up
bills with revisions and additions. Leadership
in committees is determined by the majority
political party.

265C8F14383D48D3B444B174304050C6.description:
The structures and powers of the Senate and
House are different by design. This difference
directly affects the legislative process.

408765A739844CD3B873B29E37F1B1C5.description:
Explain how the structure,
powers, and functions of both
houses of Congress affect
the policymaking process.

Structures, Powers,
and Functions of
Congress

Conducting oversight of the executive
branch, including federal agencies in the
bureaucracy

080ACAE6C9B44F68ADC8C727AE6D2F4E.description:
Enacting legislation under the authority of
the necessary and proper clause

11291E8815FC4D37A1EC29B0CFA7CE5C.description:
Creating federal courts and their
jurisdictions

4656FA5D9CB14F06A2FCC9D8A2AC6CBF.description:
Determining the process for naturalization
by which people can become citizens of
the U.S.

32E76F9E12374CF7B0784402DBE228EB.description:
Declaring war and providing the funds
necessary to maintain the armed forces

75237AD9FA90487087C6154DADA78116.description:
Passing a federal budget, raising revenue
by laying and collecting taxes, borrowing
money, and coining money

64884D714D9841D4942B7242E3B7A113.description:
The enumerated and implied powers in the
Constitution allow Congress to participate in
the public policy process by:

7A56B7B2370041B198CFB513C4244DC5.description:
Interactions in Congress are affected by the
two-party system and term-length differences.
One-third of the Senate is elected every two
years, creating a continuous legislative body.
All House members are elected every two
years.

1462E11988A144C7AD0FDDCF2BD8D57B.description:
Different membership sizes influence the
formality of debate in each chamber. Debate
in the House, which has 435 members, is more
formal than in the Senate, with 100 members.

68547A0B1A1440F28C53CEF34C99FFD8.description:
Republicanism, the democratic principle that
the will of the people is reflected in government
debates and decisions by their representatives,
is shown in the bicameral structure of
Congress. The Senate is designed to represent
states equally, while the House is designed to
represent the people.

7388DE3A010E487E9CD4F7348DAC7DB3.description:
Describe the different
structures, powers, and
functions of each house of
Congress.

B97D25997D194AC3B5DD228AAE8EA460.description:
Congress: The Senate
and the House of
Representatives

6F419B430CEB42D59B0ECA56BAEA5A51.description:
National policymaking is constrained by the
sharing of concurrent powers with state
governments.

E303550B8CF74CEF9A17C1AB7751E792.description:
The allocation of powers between national and
state governments creates multiple access
points for stakeholders and institutions to
influence public policy.

250DE5D0AF7B444189F0822C4911AF53.description:
Explain how the distribution
of powers between national
and state governments
impacts policymaking.

D52659D110B84CF7BEC9869F783418AC.description:
The Supremacy Clause gives the national
government and its laws general precedence
over states’ laws, but Supreme Court
interpretations may affect when specific
actions exceed this constitutional power.

9F5244EDAADA4BD59DFEC9950A1ABE70.description:
The Necessary and Proper Clause gives
Congress the power to make laws related
to carrying out its enumerated powers, but
Supreme Court interpretations can influence
the extent of these powers.

142BF4A6141F49F6ABF2944700D9E591.description:
The Commerce Clause gives the national
government the power to regulate interstate
commerce, but Supreme Court interpretations
can influence the extent of this power.

3CDAA7393D5B47FB8FA4F2E821BFD769.description:
The Due Process and Equal Protection Clauses
of the Fourteenth Amendment give the national
government the power to enforce protections
for any person against the states, but Supreme
Court interpretations can influence the extent
of those protections.

395AF93BD5424903B9A13BC1612BE4DF.description:
Explain how the balance
of power between national

Anti-Federalists opposed the ratification of the
Constitution and wanted more power reserved
to state governments rather than a strong
central government. Anti-Federalist writings,
including Brutus No. 1, adhered to popular
democratic theory that emphasized the
benefits of a small, decentralized republic while
warning of the dangers to personal liberty from
a large, centralized government.

Madison’s arguments in Federalist No. 10

in controlling the “mischiefs of faction,”
delegating authority to elected representatives
and dispersing power between the states and
national government.

2E89B06E6A5D4E69870193FA13AE5A98.description:
The Declaration of Independence, drafted by
Thomas Jefferson (with help from Adams and
Franklin), restates the philosophy of natural
rights, and provides a foundation for popular
sovereignty. The U.S. Constitution, drafted
by James Madison at the Constitutional
Convention in Philadelphia that was led
by George Washington (with important
contributions from Hamilton and members
of the “Grand Committee”), is an example of
a social contract and establishes a system of
limited government. The Constitution provides
the blueprint for a unique form of democratic
government in the United States.
